Date: 14 Oct 2000 10:03:37 EDT
From: Walter J. Griffiths <Walter.J.Griffiths@Dartmouth.EDU>
Source: State of Vermont, Department of Health, West Nile Fact sheet, 13
Oct 2000 [edited
<http://www.state.vt.us/health/record/westnile5.htm>

Hermit Thrush Tests Positive for West Nile Virus in Vermont
----------------------------------------------------------
BURLINGTON: The Vermont Department of Health today received notice that a
Hermit Thrush found in Putney on 29 Sep 2000 tested positive for West Nile
virus. This is the first bird found in Vermont to test positive for West
Nile virus.
"Considering that positive birds have been confirmed in surrounding states,
it was only a matter of time before a bird in Vermont tested positive for
West Nile virus," said Peter Galbraith, state epidemiologist at the Vermont
Department of Health. Given the cool weather and lack of mosquito activity,
health officials are not recommending any spraying in the Putney area.
According to Galbraith, although mosquitoes can be seen in some parts of
Vermont through the fall, it is unlikely that there will be any human cases
of West Nile virus this year. "This confirmation of [the presence of West
Nile virus is consistent with the expectation that the virus will likely
become established in the region and that mosquito surveillance, mosquito
control and precautions to prevent mosquito bites will become routine,"
said Galbraith. Vermont residents have been extraordinary in their
cooperation with the Health Department in reporting dead birds from all
over the state. Over 555 dead birds have been reported and 213 have been
sent for testing. Prior to this most recent finding, 153 birds have tested
negative.
Testing dead birds is one part of the state's West Nile virus surveillance
program. In addition, the Department of Agriculture has been trapping and
testing mosquitoes for the virus. No mosquitoes have tested positive this
year. People get West Nile virus from the bite of an infected mosquito. So
far this year, the virus has been detected in mosquitoes and birds in
several states including New Hampshire, New York, Massachusetts, New
Jersey, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Delaware, Maryland and Washington DC.
--
Walter J. Griffiths
<Walter.J.Griffiths@Dartmouth.EDU>
